          "body": "The Levitical census (26:57-62) is handled separately, as in Numbers 1-4, because Levi receives no territorial inheritance — YHWH is their inheritance (cf. Numbers 18:20). But the chapter embeds within the Levitical genealogy the names that explain the current leadership structure: Kohath begat Amram; Amram and Jochebed had Moses, Aaron, and Miriam (26:59); Aaron had Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar (26:60); Nadab and Abihu died (26:61). The genealogy explains why Eleazar, not a firstborn, now stands at Moses's side as priest (26:1) — two of Aaron's four sons were removed by divine judgment. The priestly succession is not a political appointment; it is the result of God's holiness pruning the line. The 23,000 Levites counted from a month old (26:62) represent the full worshiping community, not just warriors — their purpose is liturgical, not military, which is why the counting criterion differs."
