          "body": "Verses 64-65 are the chapter's emotional and theological climax, though they are named with austere brevity. Not one man of the Sinai census is left — except Caleb the son of Jephunneh and Joshua the son of Nun. These two names carry enormous weight for any Israelite reader. They are the two spies who brought back a minority report from Canaan forty years earlier (Numbers 13:30; 14:6-9), who said the land was conquerable because YHWH was with Israel, and who were nearly stoned by the congregation (14:10). For forty years they have watched every contemporary die in the wilderness. Now they stand at the border, the sole survivors of a generation. The author provides no emotional commentary. None is needed. The reader who has followed Numbers from chapter 1 knows what those two names mean: faithfulness to God's word, sustained across four decades of wilderness, is the only currency that purchases the land."
